My short explanation: every time you call a function, its vars get allocated on the stack. When you return from the function, you &quot;pop&quot; the stack, but all that means is that the stack pointer is now pointing to main. There is no reason to actually clear the stack memory as that would be a waste of CPU cycles. Therefore, if main() calls foo(), then foo() returns, the contents of the variables of foo() is still one frame higher on the frame stack and given the right memory address you can still access it.<p>As others point out, this is not something you should rely on. On the other hand if you are trying to overflow the stack or somehow break the program, this is definitely something to try.<p>The converse of this is that local variables of main() can be made accessibly to foo():<p><pre><code>    void foo(int *x) {
        printf(&quot;a = %d\n&quot;, *x);
    }

    void main() {
        int a = 12;
        foo(&a);
    }
</code></pre>
This of course makes sense: when you are in the middle of foo(), main()&#x27;s variables have to be stored somewhere and are accessible.<p>Edit: here&#x27;s another fun way to get <i>a</i> from foo():<p><pre><code>    void foo() {
        int *x;
        x = (int *) (&x + sizeof(int));
        printf(&quot;a = %d\n&quot;, *x);
    }

    int main() {
        int a = 12;
        foo();
        return 0;
    }</code></pre>
